:: Approach Shana [venue-trishas] {"position":"700,1700","size":"100,100"}
(set: $metShana to true)

Whenever you see Shana you are hungry. Her lovers are always speechless, beautiful, women who seem to be chosen more for their natural indifference to words, than shocked into silence, like her male companions.

She doesn't look up but knows you're there because she has read the Angelic Keys of Edward Kelly, and has such a talent for practical magick. Drinks land on the table, all whiskys, one for each of her five companions and somehow one more for you. She is yet to look up.

'Give it here,' she says.

[[Hand over the manuscript|Shana Reads]]
[[I'd rather not|Shana Refused]]


:: Approach the novelist {"position":"500,550","size":"100,100"}
There, sitting quietly at a table in the corner, you spot what you're after.

He's a novelist now, though you've known him since he was but a poet.

Between the ground you've taken and his position falls an amber monolith, through a Dean Street window; a thick and molten bar on the gnarly floor, light and distinct. If you stepped in it you could become a fossil, like the filoplume of a silent dinosaur.

You once told him that he should stick to poems.

Have you anything to lose?

[[Nothing|The novelist]]
[[Everything|The novelist]]


:: At the Corner of Dean Street and Greek Street {"position":"1200,400","size":"100,100"}
A man, not much past twenty, stands under a ginger light. At first you think he must be a dilly boy. He wears a beret and paints his nails; he is epicene and crinoline, as if he might snap at any moment.

Then you clock him for a poet that you know. A poet called Red.

[[Wait for him to speak|You wait for him to speak]]
[[Speak to him|You speak to the poet]]


:: Beaten [venue-cellar] {"position":"2200,1250","size":"100,100"}
(set: $wasBeaten to true)

Copper's short hook catches you and you're floored.

'I don't talk to liars,' he says.

As he stands on the precipice of valediction, about to finish the job, a voice shouts from the staircase, 'Salvu! Leave it! He's alright.'

It's John St. John.

Copper stops: 'He thinks he owns the place.'

'I know him. I hate him but I know him and he's sound.' John St. John's face is legible only to you, who once knew him so well. He's amused at your situation, pleased both that you're in it and that he could save you from it, and wound-up that he had to save you again.

He pulls you to your feet.

(if: $metRed is true)[He leans close as he pulls you to your feet: 'Red told Copper you had money. A manuscript worth something, he thought, the numpty. Sold you for a song, it's the French in him.']

[[He has something to tell you|St. John's Word]]


:: St. John's Word [venue-cellar] {"position":"2200,1350","size":"100,100"}
'Lackland's got a back room. The word's //Valletta//.'

Copper's gurning, more in speed than anger.

St. John leads you out: 'Next time, knock on the right door.'

(set: $confidence to $confidence - 8)

(if: $knowsCopperSecret is false)[(set: $knowsCopperSecret to true)

<div class="lore-box">
<strong>⟡ SECRET LEARNED ⟡</strong>

John St. John gave you a password: //Valletta//. For Lackland's back room.
</div>]

You surface into Dean Street like the ascent of man, having something, at least, that you didn't have before.

[[Dean Street|Dean Street]]


:: Black page {"position":"1700,200","size":"100,100"}
EXPLICIT LIBER EST.

[[PLUS. ULTRA.|Dawn]]


:: Cecil Court {"position":"300,1550","size":"100,100"}
(set: $exploredSinceFrench to true)
A light's on late in Cecil Court, leeching its scrumpy amber into the fog that's settled between shopfronts. This is the Booksellers' street. In dimmed windows you glimpse the things you covet: first impressions with uncorrected misprints, presentation copies and pirated stuff.

On your way to the amber light you pass by Watkins, long tenant of numbers 19-21, and hoary purveyor of the esoteric and occult.

[[Look in|Watkins]]


:: Watkins {"position":"300,1580","size":"100,100"}
At first you see only yourself reflected back in the window; but a moment later it fizzes into clarity, like the bubbles on tonic, and you see now through glass clear as perfect ice.

A waltz strikes up, twice-muffled, as if it came both from the inside of the bookshop and your  own inmost ear.

You watch a moment longer: from the stockroom, two brass figures appear, lifesize, dancing; Madame Blavatsky is waltzing with the Beast.

[[Waltz on to the light|O'Flatterly's shop]]


:: O'Flatterly's shop {"position":"300,1620","size":"100,100"}
The sign reads: I. O'FLATTERLY, dealer in books.

You waltz in.

Strenuously reading, Inish O'Flatterly sits at the thick wooden counter. He does not look to notice you, yet neither does his shop lack any welcome.

[[I was sent by Clegg|O'Flatterly introduction]]
[[I was told you know things|O'Flatterly introduction]]


