:: Meet Jeffrey Bernard {"position":"700,1000","size":"100,100"}
You're back on Dean Street.

From the direction of Leicester Square a man is approaching. He is walking a cow. He is Jeffrey Bernard.

He stops, and resumes a conversation you'd never begun:

'I'd very much like to wake up one morning with a cow of the Friesian variety and walk her down to Soho to the Coach and Horses, stopping on the way to buy twenty Players, ply her with vodkas until closing time, whip her off to an Indian restaurant, take her up to the Colony Room till 5.30 and then to the Yorkminster, Swiss Tavern, Three Greyhounds, get beaten up by Chinese waiters at midnight, have a row with the taxi driver, set the bed on fire, put it out with tears and then wake up on the floor. Could you then milk said cow? I doubt it.'

The cow regards you with milky indifference.

[[Ask him for advice|Jeffrey conversation]]
[[Deal with the cow|Jeffrey Bernard's Cow]]
[[Walk away|Dean Street]]


:: Milk Jeffrey Bernard's Cow {"position":"900,1300","size":"100,100"}
You lie on the Dean Street pavement like a mechanic under a chassis, take an udder in your fist and squeeze it, gingerly.

A little warm milk plashes on your lips. It tastes of grass and moonlight and something you can't name.

'This,' you think, 'is why he is unwell.'

But strangely, you feel better. The milk has settled something in you.

