:: The Night Ahead {"position":"500,50","size":"100,100"}
Autumn, 1973. 

Soho, London.


You've written a book and you've a baby at home; tonight, somehow, you'll make them both make sense. The book took much longer to make than the girl, though after an immediate, impromptu effort, you can't take much credit for her.

The girl is born now and her mother, Aoife, sits at home, with the babe in her arms. 

Home's cold; at home there's not much food. If she's told you once, she's told you again and again that there's not enough money. You are not a bad man so you've taken a job in a warehouse close to home. But it won't bring in enough, not all year. 

And so tonight, you've gone back to Soho, with a book in your bag and a sense of the place as it was, ten years ago, when //no wife, no house or land still seemed quite natural.//

You'll try, you suppose, the haunts you used to haunt and the people you knew. That'll work: it's a good book and God's a good man.

You've been thinking about the form of the aubade, the morning poem, the song of wake-me-not-so-I-might-have-dream. You've been thinking about the first love of your life; Lily, from the deepest vale of Wales.

//Forget about your book, an aubade is a song to the dawn, and the only way out of Soho is to find one.//

[[Step into the night|Dean Street]]


:: The Spanish Artist {"position":"500,800","size":"100,100"}
Benito de los Juncales del Este has a bottle of chablis, one-third-drunk, in his hand. He ushers you to a empty table, the one where the artists sat before they were too many, and all stood up to talk.

He has the eyes of a man who is happy to watch the light change.

He takes an empty glass from the table and pours.

'You're selling something,' he says. It's not a question. 'I can see it in the way you hold yourself. Like a man carrying a stone he cannot put down.'

He signals for two glasses of wine. The barman brings them without a word.

'I will tell you what I learned,' he says, 'from painting. You cannot force someone to see what you have made. You can only make it, and leave it where it might be found.'

He drinks.

'The work is yours. The seeing is theirs. Do not confuse the two, or you will go mad.'

[[He looks at you|The Painter's Gaze]]


:: The Painter's Gaze {"position":"500,900","size":"100,100"}
He looks at you like, painterly, he looked when you were his subject.

