:: Trisha's [venue-trishas] {"position":"700,1550","size":"100,100"}
(set: $confidence to $confidence + 10)
(set: $sobriety to $sobriety - 8)
(set: $exploredSinceFrench to true)
(unless: $visited is a datamap)[(set: $visited to (dm:))]
(unless: $visited contains "Trishas")[(set: $visited's Trishas to false)]
(if: $visited's Trishas is not true)[(set: $visited's Trishas to true)
<div class="first-visit-hint">TRISHA'S: HERE AT LAST.  IT WAS GOING TO HAPPEN SOONER OR LATER.</div>]

The basement stairs descend into smoke and incarnadine light. Music thuds through the walls like a second heartbeat; something with horns, something that learned its grief in America.

You push through a curtain of glass beads and the party takes you in its mouth.

The beautiful. The damned. A film star laughs too loud in one corner, mascara running like a confession. Two men in velvet argue about Warhol while a woman between them drinks from both their glasses. Somebody famous weeps in a phone booth. Somebody infamous buys champagne for strangers; the strangers accept, as strangers do.

The air tastes of perfume, secrets, cigarettes. The holy trinity.

You find a space at the bar. The bartender—silver hair, knowing eyes, the face of a woman who has heard every lie and believed none of them—slides you a drink without asking.

'On the house,' she says. 'You look like you need it.'

(if: ($alba contains $alba1) and ($alba contains $alba2) and not ($alba contains $alba3))[She leans closer, polishing a glass that is already clean.

'You're looking for something,' she says. 'I can always tell.'

She glances toward the stairs—the ones that lead back up, back out, back to the street.

'Some people find what they need on the way out. When the night's nearly spent. When the light begins to change.'

She moves away. Her words remain, like coins dropped in a well. //The stairs. The dawn.//]
(else:)[You drink. The party roars. For a moment—the width of a breath—you feel like you belong here.

Then it passes, and you remember the manuscript in your bag. You remember everything.]

In the far corner, beneath a painting of something anatomically speculative, a woman holds court. She sits like a monument, like something the Romans left behind. Broad. Immovable. Magnificent. Around her, a circle of supplicants lean in like flowers toward an ugly sun.

Beside her, tangled on a banquette, two young lovers: a dark-haired boy with paint on his cuffs, a girl with cropped hair and a sailor's tattoo. They are oblivious to everything but each other. They are speaking a language that has only two native speakers.

You know who the woman is. Everyone knows. Shana. Patron, critic, destroyer. They say she made three careers and ended a dozen, all before breakfast. They say she eats writers like you for breakfast. They say a lot of things.

(if: $metShana is false)[[[Approach Shana|Approach Shana]]]

(if: $metShana is true)[<div class="venue-exhausted">You've spoken to Shana. Nothing more to do here but drink and watch.</div>]

(if: not ($haunts contains $haunt8))[<span class="missed-haunt">You missed a haunt</span>]

(if: $knowsRonnies is true and $completedSetlist is false)[[[Ronnie Scott's is nearby.|Ronnie Scott's]]]
[[Back to Dean Street|Dean Street]]


:: Turn to Copper {"position":"1600,850","size":"100,100"}
'Salvu Copper' is a name you know and now you're putting a face to it.

Since the Twins went down in '68, his work's been easier. He's run his little fiefdom – pornography, strip clubs, hookers (the sorts of work that old fashioned East End crooks will swear blind they don't touch) – very nicely, though lately he's feeling the heat.

At the far end of the cellar, at a simple wooden table, sits 'Quiet' Frankie Muscat, who seems to you like nothing so much as a planet, the sort of man with moons. Yes, he is big, but his gravity comes, mostly, from his silence and a sense of power unused.

Opposite him (and her presence surprises you) is a poet you know, an American girl who comes from banking money, called Ashton Granger. You agreed long ago to pretend not to notice each other, should you accidentally meet. She twirls her hair and scribbles without looking at the page, and gives Quiet Frankie a kind of angry come-hither look.

Copper speaks:

'What have you got to say for yourself?'

(if: $knowsCopperWord)[[[Tell Copper: "I SAID HELLO."|Copper accepts]]
[[Say nothing|Copper confronts]]]
(else:)[[[Say nothing|Copper confronts]]]


